x4freetext: PD-300 Neutron Generator
About 6 gram of Sm2O3 powder of natural isotopic
composition (>99.99% pure, TCI (Shanghai) Development
Co., Ltd.) was pressed at 10 t/cm2, and 2.0 cm in
diameter was obtained. Two such pellets were
prepared. Thickness of each sample was determined by
weighing and measuring the diameter of foil, and the
thickness of samples was 0.118 and 0.136 cm. Monitor
foils of Nb (99.99% pure, 0.5 mm thick) and Al
(99.999% pure, 0.3 mm thick) of the same diameter as
the pellets were then attached in front and at the
back of each sample.
An effective deuteron beam energy of 134 keV
and beam current of 260 uA. The tritium-titanium (T-
Ti) target was 2.38 mg/cm2 thick.
A high-purity germanium (HPGe) detector with a
relative efficiency of 68% and an energy resolution
of 1.69 keV at 1332 keV for 60Co. The distance
between the sample and the detector was about 3-9 cm.
The Au-Si surface barrier detector used in 135
degree accompanying a-particle tube was at a distance
of 110 cm from the target.
Irradiation of the samples was lasted about 2
hours with a yield about 3 to 4E10 n/(4pi*s). The
groups of samples were placed at 0 and 135 degree
angle relative to the beam direction and centered
about the T-Ti target at distances of about 5 cm.
T1/2=10.152 d in the article is typo and should read
10.15(2) d which was used in the cross section
calculation.
In the calculations,
the cross sections for the 93Nb(n,2n)92mNb and
27Al(n,a)24Na monitor reactions were obtained by
interpolating the evaluated values of the literature.
Corrections were made for the self-absorption of the
sample at a given gamma-energy, the coincidence sum
effect of cascade gamma-rays in the investigated
nuclide and in the counting geometry.
Total uncertainty.
Counting statistics 0.1-42%
Standard cross sections 0.5-1.5%
Isotopic abundance about 0.2-2.3%
Detector efficiency 2.0-3.0%
Weight of samples 0.1%
Self-absorption of gamma-ray about 0.5%
Relative gamma-ray intensity 1.0-5.7%
Half-life 0.01-3.9%
Coincidence sum effect of cascade
gamma-rays 0-6.5%
Uncertainties of irradiation,
cooling and measuring times 0.1-1.0%
